[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] In general, the study of heat conduction is based on several principles.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Heat flow is a form of energy flow, and as such it is meaningful to speak of the time rate of flow of heat into a region of space.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The heat equation is a consequence of Fourier's law of conduction (see heat conduction).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] If the medium is not the whole space, in order to solve the heat equation uniquely we also need to specify boundary conditions for *u*.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] To determine uniqueness of solutions in the whole space it is necessary to assume additional conditions, for example an exponential bound on the growth of solutions or a sign condition (nonnegative solutions are unique by a result of David Widder).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Solutions of the heat equation are characterized by a gradual smoothing of the initial temperature distribution by the flow of heat from warmer to colder areas of an object.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Generally, many different states and starting conditions will tend toward the same stable equilibrium.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] As a consequence, to reverse the solution and conclude something about earlier times or initial conditions from the present heat distribution is very inaccurate except over the shortest of time periods.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The heat equation is the prototypical example of a parabolic partial differential equation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] where the Laplace operator, denoted as either Δ or as ∇2 (the divergence of the gradient), is taken in the spatial variables.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The heat equation governs heat diffusion, as well as other diffusive processes, such as particle diffusion or the propagation of action potential in nerve cells.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Although they are not diffusive in nature, some quantum mechanics problems are also governed by a mathematical analog of the heat equation (see below).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] It also can be used to model some phenomena arising in finance, like the Black–Scholes or the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck processes.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The equation, and various non-linear analogues, has also been used in image analysis.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The heat equation is, technically, in violation of special relativity, because its solutions involve instantaneous propagation of a disturbance.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Some models of nonlinear heat conduction (which are also parabolic equations) have solutions with finite heat transmission speed.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The function *u* above represents temperature of a body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Alternatively, it is sometimes convenient to change units and represent *u* as the heat density of a medium.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Since heat density is proportional to temperature in a homogeneous medium, the heat equation is still obeyed in the new units.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Suppose that a body obeys the heat equation and, in addition, generates its own heat per unit volume (e.g., in watts/litre - W/L) at a rate given by a known function *q* varying in space and time.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] For example, a tungsten light bulb filament generates heat, so it would have a positive nonzero value for *q* when turned on.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] While the light is turned off, the value of *q* for the tungsten filament would be zero.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The following solution technique for the heat equation was proposed by Joseph Fourier in his treatise *Théorie analytique de la chaleur*, published in 1822.
