[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] As the prototypical parabolic partial differential equation, the heat equation is among the most widely studied topics in pure mathematics, and its analysis is regarded as fundamental to the broader field of partial differential equations.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The heat equation can also be considered on Riemannian manifolds, leading to many geometric applications.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Following work of Subbaramiah Minakshisundaram and Åke Pleijel, the heat equation is closely related with spectral geometry.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] A seminal nonlinear variant of the heat equation was introduced to differential geometry by James Eells and Joseph Sampson in 1964, inspiring the introduction of the Ricci flow by Richard Hamilton in 1982 and culminating in the proof of the Poincaré conjecture by Grigori Perelman in 2003.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Certain solutions of the heat equation known as heat kernels provide subtle information about the region on which they are defined, as exemplified through their application to the Atiyah–Singer index theorem.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The heat equation, along with variants thereof, is also important in many fields of science and applied mathematics.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] In probability theory, the heat equation is connected with the study of random walks and Brownian motion via the Fokker–Planck equation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The Black–Scholes equation of financial mathematics is a small variant of the heat equation, and the Schrödinger equation of quantum mechanics can be regarded as a heat equation in imaginary time.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] In image analysis, the heat equation is sometimes used to resolve pixelation and to identify edges.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Following Robert Richtmyer and John von Neumann's introduction of artificial viscosity methods, solutions of heat equations have been useful in the mathematical formulation of hydrodynamical shocks.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Solutions of the heat equation have also been given much attention in the numerical analysis literature, beginning in the 1950s with work of Jim Douglas, D.W.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Both *c* and *P* are functions of position and time.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] *D* is the diffusion coefficient that controls the speed of the diffusive process, and is typically expressed in meters squared over second.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] If the diffusion coefficient *D* is not constant, but depends on the concentration *c* (or *P* in the second case), then one gets the nonlinear diffusion equation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] where B is the Wiener process (standard Brownian motion).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] where $\delta$ is the Dirac delta function.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] where *i* is the imaginary unit, *ħ* is the reduced Planck constant, and *ψ* is the wave function of the particle.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Remark: this analogy between quantum mechanics and diffusion is a purely formal one.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Physically, the evolution of the wave function satisfying the Schrödinger equation might have an origin other than diffusion.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] A direct practical application of the heat equation, in conjunction with Fourier theory, in spherical coordinates, is the prediction of thermal transfer profiles and the measurement of the thermal diffusivity in polymers (Unsworth and Duarte).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] This dual theoretical-experimental method is applicable to rubber, various other polymeric materials of practical interest, and microfluids.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] where *T*0 is the initial temperature of the sphere and TS the temperature at the surface of the sphere, of radius L.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] This equation has also found applications in protein energy transfer and thermal modeling in biophysics.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The heat equation arises in a number of phenomena and is often used in financial mathematics in the modeling of options.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The Black–Scholes option pricing model's differential equation can be transformed into the heat equation allowing relatively easy solutions from a familiar body of mathematics.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Many of the extensions to the simple option models do not have closed form solutions and thus must be solved numerically to obtain a modeled option price.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The equation describing pressure diffusion in a porous medium is identical in form with the heat equation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] Diffusion problems dealing with Dirichlet, Neumann and Robin boundary conditions have closed form analytic solutions (Thambynayagam 2011).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The heat equation is also widely used in image analysis (Perona & Malik 1990) and in machine learning as the driving theory behind scale-space or graph Laplacian methods.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] The heat equation can be efficiently solved numerically using the implicit Crank–Nicolson method of (Crank & Nicolson 1947).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] This method can be extended to many of the models with no closed form solution, see for instance (Wilmott, Howison & Dewynne 1995).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-equation] An abstract form of heat equation on manifolds provides a major approach to the Atiyah–Singer index theorem, and has led to much further work on heat equations in Riemannian geometry.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A **heat exchanger** is a system used to transfer heat between a source and a working fluid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Heat exchangers are used in both cooling and heating processes.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The fluids may be separated by a solid wall to prevent mixing or they may be in direct contact.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] They are widely used in space heating, refrigeration, air conditioning, power stations, chemical plants, petrochemical plants, petroleum refineries, natural-gas processing, and sewage treatment.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The classic example of a heat exchanger is found in an internal combustion engine in which a circulating fluid known as engine coolant flows through radiator coils and air flows past the coils, which cools the coolant and heats the incoming air.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Another example is the heat sink, which is a passive heat exchanger that transfers the heat generated by an electronic or a mechanical device to a fluid medium, often air or a liquid coolant.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] There are three primary classifications of heat exchangers according to their flow arrangement.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In *parallel-flow* heat exchangers, the two fluids enter the exchanger at the same end, and travel in parallel to one another to the other side.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In *counter-flow* heat exchangers the fluids enter the exchanger from opposite ends.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The counter current design is the most efficient, in that it can transfer the most heat from the heat (transfer) medium per unit mass due to the fact that the average temperature difference along any unit length is *higher*.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In a *cross-flow* heat exchanger, the fluids travel roughly perpendicular to one another through the exchanger.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] For efficiency, heat exchangers are designed to maximize the surface area of the wall between the two fluids, while minimizing resistance to fluid flow through the exchanger.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The exchanger's performance can also be affected by the addition of fins or corrugations in one or both directions, which increase surface area and may channel fluid flow or induce turbulence.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The driving temperature across the heat transfer surface varies with position, but an appropriate mean temperature can be defined.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In most simple systems this is the "log mean temperature difference" (LMTD).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Sometimes direct knowledge of the LMTD is not available and the NTU method is used.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] By maximum operating temperature, heat exchangers can be divided into low-temperature and high-temperature ones.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The former work up to 500–650 °C depending on the industry and generally do not require special design and material considerations.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The latter work up to 1000 or even 1400 °C.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Double pipe heat exchangers are the simplest exchangers used in industries.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] On one hand, these heat exchangers are cheap for both design and maintenance, making them a good choice for small industries.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] On the other hand, their low efficiency coupled with the high space occupied in large scales, has led modern industries to use more efficient heat exchangers like shell and tube or plate.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] However, since double pipe heat exchangers are simple, they are used to teach heat exchanger design basics to students as the fundamental rules for all heat exchangers are the same.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] When one fluid flows through the smaller pipe, the other flows through the annular gap between the two pipes.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] These flows may be parallel or counter-flows in a double pipe heat exchanger.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] (a) Parallel flow, where both hot and cold liquids enter the heat exchanger from the same side, flow in the same direction and exit at the same end.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This configuration is preferable when the two fluids are intended to reach exactly the same temperature, as it reduces thermal stress and produces a more uniform rate of heat transfer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] (b) Counter-flow, where hot and cold fluids enter opposite sides of the heat exchanger, flow in opposite directions, and exit at opposite ends.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This configuration is preferable when the objective is to maximize heat transfer between the fluids, as it creates a larger temperature differential when used under otherwise similar conditions.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The figure above illustrates the parallel and counter-flow flow directions of the fluid exchanger.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In a shell-and-tube heat exchanger, two fluids at different temperatures flow through the heat exchanger.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] One of the fluids flows through the tube side and the other fluid flows outside the tubes, but inside the shell (shell side).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Baffles are used to support the tubes, direct the fluid flow to the tubes in an approximately natural manner, and maximize the turbulence of the shell fluid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] There are many various kinds of baffles, and the choice of baffle form, spacing, and geometry depends on the allowable flow rate of the drop in shell-side force, the need for tube support, and the flow-induced vibrations.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] There are several variations of shell-and-tube exchangers available; the differences lie in the arrangement of flow configurations and details of construction.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In application to cool air with shell-and-tube technology (such as intercooler / charge air cooler for combustion engines), fins can be added on the tubes to increase heat transfer area on air side and create a tubes & fins configuration.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A plate heat exchanger consists of multiple thin metal plates stacked in a compact bundle.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Gaskets seal the spaces between each pair of adjacent plates, creating two independent flow channels.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This design allows two different fluids to flow through alternate channels without mixing.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The plates are secured together using welding and bolting methods to ensure structural integrity and prevent leakage.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The corrugated surface patterns on the plates serve two critical functions: they increase the surface area available for heat transfer and create turbulent flow that enhances thermal performance.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In counter-current configuration, the two fluids flow in opposite directions through adjacent channels, which maximizes the temperature difference available for heat exchange and improves efficiency.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Gaskets positioned between the outer frame plates and inner pressure plates create a reliable seal that prevents cross-contamination.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The distribution design ensures fluid flows across the entire heat transfer surface, preventing stagnant zones where deposits might accumulate.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Plate heat exchangers are manufactured in various configurations including plate and frame, plate and shell, and spiral designs with different plate depths, sizes, and corrugation patterns to accommodate specific applications and performance requirements.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Condensers and Boilers Heat exchangers using a two-phase heat transfer system are condensers, boilers and evaporators.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Condensers are instruments that take and cool hot gas or vapor to the point of condensation and transform the gas into a liquid form.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The point at which liquid transforms to gas is called vaporization and vice versa is called condensation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Surface condenser is the most common type of condenser where it includes a water supply device.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Figure 5 below displays a two-pass surface condenser.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The pressure of steam at the turbine outlet is low where the steam density is very low where the flow rate is very high.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] To prevent a decrease in pressure in the movement of steam from the turbine to condenser, the condenser unit is placed underneath and connected to the turbine.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Inside the tubes the cooling water runs in a parallel way, while steam moves in a vertical downward position from the wide opening at the top and travel through the tube.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Furthermore, boilers are categorized as initial application of heat exchangers.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The word steam generator was regularly used to describe a boiler unit where a hot liquid stream is the source of heat rather than the combustion products.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Depending on the dimensions and configurations the boilers are manufactured.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Several boilers are only able to produce hot fluid while on the other hand the others are manufactured for steam production.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Shell and tube heat exchangers consist of a series of tubes which contain fluid that must be either heated or cooled.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A second fluid runs over the tubes that are being heated or cooled so that it can either provide the heat or absorb the heat required.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A set of tubes is called the tube bundle and can be made up of several types of tubes: plain, longitudinally finned, etc.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Shell and tube heat exchangers are typically used for high-pressure applications (with pressures greater than 30 bar and temperatures greater than 260 °C).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This is because the shell and tube heat exchangers are robust due to their shape.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Several thermal design features must be considered when designing the tubes in the shell and tube heat exchangers: There can be many variations on the shell and tube design.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Typically, the ends of each tube are connected to plenums (sometimes called water boxes) through holes in tubesheets.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The tubes may be straight or bent in the shape of a U, called U-tubes.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Fixed tube liquid-cooled heat exchangers especially suitable for marine and harsh applications can be assembled with brass shells, copper tubes, brass baffles, and forged brass integral end hubs.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Another type of heat exchanger is the plate heat exchanger.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] These exchangers are composed of many thin, slightly separated plates that have very large surface areas and small fluid flow passages for heat transfer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Advances in gasket and brazing technology have made the plate-type heat exchanger increasingly practical.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In HVAC applications, large heat exchangers of this type are called *plate-and-frame*; when used in open loops, these heat exchangers are normally of the gasket type to allow periodic disassembly, cleaning, and inspection.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] There are many types of permanently bonded plate heat exchangers, such as dip-brazed, vacuum-brazed, and welded plate varieties, and they are often specified for closed-loop applications such as refrigeration.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Plate heat exchangers also differ in the types of plates that are used, and in the configurations of those plates.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Some plates may be stamped with "chevron", dimpled, or other patterns, where others may have machined fins and/or grooves.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] When compared to shell and tube exchangers, the stacked-plate arrangement typically has lower volume and cost.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Another difference between the two is that plate exchangers typically serve low to medium pressure fluids, compared to medium and high pressures of shell and tube.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A third and important difference is that plate exchangers employ more countercurrent flow rather than cross current flow, which allows lower approach temperature differences, high temperature changes, and increased efficiencies.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A third type of heat exchanger is a plate and shell heat exchanger, which combines plate heat exchanger with shell and tube heat exchanger technologies.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The heart of the heat exchanger contains a fully welded circular plate pack made by pressing and cutting round plates and welding them together.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Nozzles carry flow in and out of the platepack (the 'Plate side' flowpath).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The fully welded platepack is assembled into an outer shell that creates a second flowpath (the 'Shell side').
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Plate and shell technology offers high heat transfer, high pressure, high operating temperature, compact size, low fouling and close approach temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In particular, it does completely without gaskets, which provides security against leakage at high pressures and temperatures.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A fourth type of heat exchanger uses an intermediate fluid or solid store to hold heat, which is then moved to the other side of the heat exchanger to be released.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Two examples of this are adiabatic wheels, which consist of a large wheel with fine threads rotating through the hot and cold fluids, and fluid heat exchangers.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This type of heat exchanger uses "sandwiched" passages containing fins to increase the effectiveness of the unit.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The designs include crossflow and counterflow coupled with various fin configurations such as straight fins, offset fins and wavy fins.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Plate and fin heat exchangers are usually made of aluminum alloys, which provide high heat transfer efficiency.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The material enables the system to operate at a lower temperature difference and reduce the weight of the equipment.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Plate and fin heat exchangers are mostly used for low temperature services such as natural gas, helium and oxygen liquefaction plants, air separation plants and transport industries such as motor and aircraft engines.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The usage of fins in a tube-based heat exchanger is common when one of the working fluids is a low-pressure gas, and is typical for heat exchangers that operate using ambient air, such as automotive radiators and HVAC air condensers.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Fins dramatically increase the surface area with which heat can be exchanged, which improves the efficiency of conducting heat to a fluid with very low thermal conductivity, such as air.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The fins are typically made from aluminium or copper since they must conduct heat from the tube along the length of the fins, which are usually very thin.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Stacked-fin or spiral-wound construction can be used for the tubes inside shell-and-tube heat exchangers when high efficiency thermal transfer to a gas is required.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In electronics cooling, heat sinks, particularly those using heat pipes, can have a stacked-fin construction.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A pillow plate heat exchanger is commonly used in the dairy industry for cooling milk in large direct-expansion stainless steel bulk tanks.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Nearly the entire surface area of a tank can be integrated with this heat exchanger, without gaps that would occur between pipes welded to the exterior of the tank.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Pillow plates can also be constructed as flat plates that are stacked inside a tank.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The relatively flat surface of the plates allows easy cleaning, especially in sterile applications.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The pillow plate can be constructed using either a thin sheet of metal welded to the thicker surface of a tank or vessel, or two thin sheets welded together.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The surface of the plate is welded with a regular pattern of dots or a serpentine pattern of weld lines.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] After welding the enclosed space is pressurised with sufficient force to cause the thin metal to bulge out around the welds, providing a space for heat exchanger liquids to flow, and creating a characteristic appearance of a swelled pillow formed out of metal.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A waste heat recovery unit (WHRU) is a heat exchanger that recovers heat from a hot gas stream while transferring it to a working medium, typically water or oils.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The hot gas stream can be the exhaust gas from a gas turbine or a diesel engine or a waste gas from industry or refinery.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Large systems with high volume and temperature gas streams, typical in industry, can benefit from steam Rankine cycle (SRC) in a waste heat recovery unit, but these cycles are too expensive for small systems.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The recovery of heat from low temperature systems requires different working fluids than steam.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] An organic Rankine cycle (ORC) waste heat recovery unit can be more efficient at low temperature range using refrigerants that boil at lower temperatures than water.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Typical organic refrigerants are ammonia, pentafluoropropane (R-245fa and R-245ca), and toluene.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The refrigerant is boiled by the heat source in the evaporator to produce super-heated vapor.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This fluid is expanded in the turbine to convert thermal energy to kinetic energy, that is converted to electricity in the electrical generator.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This energy transfer process decreases the temperature of the refrigerant that, in turn, condenses.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The cycle is closed and completed using a pump to send the fluid back to the evaporator.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Another type of heat exchanger is called "(dynamic) scraped surface heat exchanger".
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This is mainly used for heating or cooling with high-viscosity products, crystallization processes, evaporation and high-fouling applications.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Long running times are achieved due to the continuous scraping of the surface, thus avoiding fouling and achieving a sustainable heat transfer rate during the process.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In addition to heating up or cooling down fluids in just a single phase, heat exchangers can be used either to heat a liquid to evaporate (or boil) it or used as condensers to cool a vapor and condense it to a liquid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In chemical plants and refineries, reboilers used to heat incoming feed for distillation towers are often heat exchangers.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Distillation set-ups typically use condensers to condense distillate vapors back into liquid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Power plants that use steam-driven turbines commonly use heat exchangers to boil water into steam.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Heat exchangers or similar units for producing steam from water are often called boilers or steam generators.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In the nuclear power plants called pressurized water reactors, special large heat exchangers pass heat from the primary (reactor plant) system to the secondary (steam plant) system, producing steam from water in the process.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] All fossil-fueled and nuclear power plants using steam-driven turbines have surface condensers to convert the exhaust steam from the turbines into condensate (water) for re-use.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] To conserve energy and cooling capacity in chemical and other plants, regenerative heat exchangers can transfer heat from a stream that must be cooled to another stream that must be heated, such as distillate cooling and reboiler feed pre-heating.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This term can also refer to heat exchangers that contain a material within their structure that has a change of phase.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This is usually a solid to liquid phase due to the small volume difference between these states.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This change of phase effectively acts as a buffer because it occurs at a constant temperature but still allows for the heat exchanger to accept additional heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] One example where this has been investigated is for use in high power aircraft electronics.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Heat exchangers functioning in multiphase flow regimes may be subject to the Ledinegg instability.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Direct contact heat exchangers involve heat transfer between hot and cold streams of two phases in the absence of a separating wall.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Most direct contact heat exchangers fall under the Gas – Liquid category, where heat is transferred between a gas and liquid in the form of drops, films or sprays.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Such types of heat exchangers are used predominantly in air conditioning, humidification, industrial hot water heating, water cooling and condensing plants.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Microchannel heat exchangers are multi-pass parallel flow heat exchangers consisting of three main elements: manifolds (inlet and outlet), multi-port tubes with the hydraulic diameters smaller than 1mm, and fins.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] All the elements usually are brazed together using a controllable atmosphere brazing process.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Microchannel heat exchangers are characterized by high heat transfer ratio, low refrigerant charges, compact size, and lower airside pressure drops compared to finned tube heat exchangers.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Microchannel heat exchangers are widely used in automotive industry as the car radiators, and as condenser, evaporator, and cooling/heating coils in HVAC industry.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] One of the widest uses of heat exchangers is for refrigeration and air conditioning.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This class of heat exchangers is commonly called *air coils*, or just *coils* due to their often-serpentine internal tubing, or condensers in the case of refrigeration, and are typically of the finned tube type.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Liquid-to-air, or air-to-liquid HVAC coils are typically of modified crossflow arrangement.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In vehicles, heat coils are often called heater cores.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] On the liquid side of these heat exchangers, the common fluids are water, a water-glycol solution, steam, or a refrigerant.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] For *heating coils*, hot water and steam are the most common, and this heated fluid is supplied by boilers, for example.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] For *cooling coils*, chilled water and refrigerant are most common.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Chilled water is supplied from a chiller that is potentially located very far away, but refrigerant must come from a nearby condensing unit.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] When a refrigerant is used, the cooling coil is the evaporator, and the heating coil is the condenser in the vapor-compression refrigeration cycle.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] HVAC coils that use this direct-expansion of refrigerants are commonly called *DX coils*.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Some *DX coils* are "microchannel" type.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] On the air side of HVAC coils a significant difference exists between those used for heating, and those for cooling.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Due to psychrometrics, air that is cooled often has moisture condensing out of it, except with extremely dry air flows.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Heating some air increases that airflow's capacity to hold water.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] So heating coils need not consider moisture condensation on their air-side, but cooling coils *must* be adequately designed and selected to handle their particular *latent* (moisture) as well as the *sensible* (cooling) loads.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The water that is removed is called *condensate*.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] For many climates, water or steam HVAC coils can be exposed to freezing conditions.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Because water expands upon freezing, these somewhat expensive and difficult to replace thin-walled heat exchangers can easily be damaged or destroyed by just one freeze.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] As such, freeze protection of coils is a major concern of HVAC designers, installers, and operators.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The introduction of indentations placed within the heat exchange fins controlled condensation, allowing water molecules to remain in the cooled air.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The heat exchangers in direct-combustion furnaces, typical in many residences, are not 'coils'.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] They are, instead, gas-to-air heat exchangers that are typically made of stamped steel sheet metal.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The combustion products pass on one side of these heat exchangers, and air to heat on the other.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A *cracked heat exchanger* is therefore a dangerous situation that requires immediate attention because combustion products may enter living space.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] These have been used in the nuclear industry as a method for exchanging heat in a sodium system for large liquid metal fast breeder reactors since the early 1970s, using an HCHE device invented by Charles E.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] There are several simple methods for designing HCHE for all types of manufacturing industries, such as using the Ramachandra K.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Patil (et al.) method from India and the Scott S.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Haraburda method from the United States.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] However, these are based upon assumptions of estimating inside heat transfer coefficient, predicting flow around the outside of the coil, and upon constant heat flux.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A modification to the perpendicular flow of the typical HCHE involves the replacement of shell with another coiled tube, allowing the two fluids to flow parallel to one another, and which requires the use of different design calculations.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] These are the Spiral Heat Exchangers (SHE), which may refer to a helical (coiled) tube configuration, more generally, the term refers to a pair of flat surfaces that are coiled to form the two channels in a counter-flow arrangement.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Each of the two channels has one long curved path.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A pair of fluid ports are connected tangentially to the outer arms of the spiral, and axial ports are common, but optional.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The main advantage of the SHE is its highly efficient use of space.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This attribute is often leveraged and partially reallocated to gain other improvements in performance, according to well known tradeoffs in heat exchanger design.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] (A notable tradeoff is capital cost vs operating cost.) A compact SHE may be used to have a smaller footprint and thus lower all-around capital costs, or an oversized SHE may be used to have less pressure drop, less pumping energy, higher thermal efficiency, and lower energy costs.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The distance between the sheets in the spiral channels is maintained by using spacer studs that were welded prior to rolling.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Once the main spiral pack has been rolled, alternate top and bottom edges are welded and each end closed by a gasketed flat or conical cover bolted to the body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This ensures no mixing of the two fluids occurs.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Any leakage is from the periphery cover to the atmosphere, or to a passage that contains the same fluid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Spiral heat exchangers are often used in the heating of fluids that contain solids and thus tend to foul the inside of the heat exchanger.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The low pressure drop lets the SHE handle fouling more easily.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The SHE uses a “self cleaning” mechanism, whereby fouled surfaces cause a localized increase in fluid velocity, thus increasing the drag (or fluid friction) on the fouled surface, thus helping to dislodge the blockage and keep the heat exchanger clean.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] "The internal walls that make up the heat transfer surface are often rather thick, which makes the SHE very robust, and able to last a long time in demanding environments." They are also easily cleaned, opening out like an oven where any buildup of foulant can be removed by pressure washing.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Self-cleaning water filters are used to keep the system clean and running without the need to shut down or replace cartridges and bags.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The Spiral heat exchanger is good for applications such as pasteurization, digester heating, heat recovery, pre-heating (see: recuperator), and effluent cooling.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] For sludge treatment, SHEs are generally smaller than other types of heat exchangers.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Due to the many variables involved, selecting optimal heat exchangers is challenging.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Hand calculations are possible, but many iterations are typically needed.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] As such, heat exchangers are most often selected via computer programs, either by system designers, who are typically engineers, or by equipment vendors.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] To select an appropriate heat exchanger, the system designers (or equipment vendors) would firstly consider the design limitations for each heat exchanger type.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Small diameter coils can withstand the higher pressures required by the new generation of environmentally friendlier refrigerants.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Two small diameter coil technologies are currently available for air conditioning and refrigeration products: copper microgroove and brazed aluminum microchannel.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Choosing the right heat exchanger (HX) requires some knowledge of the different heat exchanger types, as well as the environment where the unit must operate.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Typically in the manufacturing industry, several differing types of heat exchangers are used for just one process or system to derive the final product.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] For example, a kettle HX for pre-heating, a double pipe HX for the 'carrier' fluid and a plate and frame HX for final cooling.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] With sufficient knowledge of heat exchanger types and operating requirements, an appropriate selection can be made to optimise the process.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Online monitoring of commercial heat exchangers is done by tracking the overall heat transfer coefficient.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The overall heat transfer coefficient tends to decline over time due to fouling.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] By periodically calculating the overall heat transfer coefficient from exchanger flow rates and temperatures, the owner of the heat exchanger can estimate when cleaning the heat exchanger is economically attractive.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Integrity inspection of plate and tubular heat exchanger can be tested in situ by the conductivity or helium gas methods.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] These methods confirm the integrity of the plates or tubes to prevent any cross contamination and the condition of the gaskets.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Mechanical integrity monitoring of heat exchanger tubes may be conducted through Nondestructive methods such as eddy current testing.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Fouling occurs when impurities deposit on the heat exchange surface.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The rate of heat exchanger fouling is determined by the rate of particle deposition less re-entrainment/suppression.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This model was originally proposed in 1959 by Kern and Seaton.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Plate and frame heat exchangers can be disassembled and cleaned periodically.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Tubular heat exchangers can be cleaned by such methods as acid cleaning, sandblasting, high-pressure water jet, bullet cleaning, or drill rods.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In large-scale cooling water systems for heat exchangers, water treatment such as purification, addition of chemicals, and testing, is used to minimize fouling of the heat exchange equipment.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Other water treatment is also used in steam systems for power plants, etc. to minimize fouling and corrosion of the heat exchange and other equipment.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] A variety of companies have started using water borne oscillations technology to prevent biofouling.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Without the use of chemicals, this type of technology has helped in providing a low-pressure drop in heat exchangers.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The design and manufacturing of heat exchangers has numerous regulations, which vary according to the region in which they will be used.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Design and manufacturing codes include: ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (US); PD 5500 (UK); BS 1566 (UK); EN 13445 (EU); CODAP (French); Pressure Equipment Safety Regulations 2016 (PER) (UK); Pressure Equipment Directive (EU); NORSOK (Norwegian); TEMA; API 12; and API 560.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The human nasal passages serve as a heat exchanger, with cool air being inhaled and warm air being exhaled.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Its effectiveness can be demonstrated by putting the hand in front of the face and exhaling, first through the nose and then through the mouth.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Air exhaled through the nose is substantially cooler.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This effect can be enhanced with clothing, by, for example, wearing a scarf over the face while breathing in cold weather.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In species that have external testes (such as human), the artery to the testis is surrounded by a mesh of veins called the pampiniform plexus.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This cools the blood heading to the testes, while reheating the returning blood.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] "Countercurrent" heat exchangers occur naturally in the circulatory systems of fish, whales and other marine mammals.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Arteries to the skin carrying warm blood are intertwined with veins from the skin carrying cold blood, causing the warm arterial blood to exchange heat with the cold venous blood.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This reduces the overall heat loss in cold water.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Heat exchangers are also present in the tongues of baleen whales as large volumes of water flow through their mouths.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Wading birds use a similar system to limit heat losses from their body through their legs into the water.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Carotid rete is a counter-current heat exchanging organ in some ungulates.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The blood ascending the carotid arteries on its way to the brain, flows via a network of vessels where heat is discharged to the veins of cooler blood descending from the nasal passages.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Humans with other primates lack a carotid rete.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Heat exchangers are widely used in industry both for cooling and heating large scale industrial processes.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The type and size of heat exchanger used can be tailored to suit a process depending on the type of fluid, its phase, temperature, density, viscosity, pressures, chemical composition and various other thermodynamic properties.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In many industrial processes there is waste of energy or a heat stream that is being exhausted, heat exchangers can be used to recover this heat and put it to use by heating a different stream in the process.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This practice saves a lot of money in industry, as the heat supplied to other streams from the heat exchangers would otherwise come from an external source that is more expensive and more harmful to the environment.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In waste water treatment, heat exchangers play a vital role in maintaining optimal temperatures within anaerobic digesters to promote the growth of microbes that remove pollutants.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Common types of heat exchangers used in this application are the double pipe heat exchanger as well as the plate and frame heat exchanger.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] In commercial aircraft heat exchangers are used to take heat from the engine's oil system to heat cold fuel.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] This improves fuel efficiency, as well as reduces the possibility of water entrapped in the fuel freezing in components.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] Estimated at US$17.5 billion in 2021, the global demand of heat exchangers is expected to experience robust growth of about 5% annually over the next years.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] The market value is expected to reach US$27 billion by 2030.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p01] With an expanding desire for environmentally friendly options and increased development of offices, retail sectors, and public buildings, market expansion is due to grow.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p02] A simple heat exchange might be thought of as two straight pipes with fluid flow, which are thermally connected.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p02] Temperature profiles for the pipes are $T_{1}(x)$ and $T_{2}(x)$ where *x* is the distance along the pipe.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p02] Assume a steady state, so that the temperature profiles are not functions of time.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p02] Assume also that the only transfer of heat from a small volume of fluid in one pipe is to the fluid element in the other pipe at the same position, i.e., there is no transfer of heat along a pipe due to temperature differences in that pipe.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p02] This change in internal energy results in a change in the temperature of the fluid element.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p02] Since the system is in a steady state, there are no partial derivatives of temperature with respect to time, and since there is no heat transfer along the pipe, there are no second derivatives in *x* as is found in the heat equation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p02] and *A* and *B* are two as yet undetermined constants of integration.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p02] Let $T_{10}$ and $T_{20}$ be the temperatures at x=0 and let $T_{1L}$ and $T_{2L}$ be the temperatures at the end of the pipe at x=L.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p02] Choosing any two of the temperatures above eliminates the constants of integration, letting us find the other four temperatures.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p02] By the conservation of energy, the sum of the two energies is zero.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-exchanger-p02] The quantity ${\overline {T}}_{2}-{\overline {T}}_{1}$ is known as the *Log mean temperature difference*, and is a measure of the effectiveness of the heat exchanger in transferring heat energy.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat conduction, also called diffusion, is the direct microscopic exchanges of kinetic energy of particles (such as molecules) or quasiparticles (such as lattice waves) through the boundary between two systems.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] When an object is at a different temperature from another body or its surroundings, heat flows so that the body and the surroundings reach the same temperature, at which point they are in thermal equilibrium.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Such spontaneous heat transfer always occurs from a region of high temperature to another region of lower temperature, as described in the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat convection occurs when the bulk flow of a fluid (gas or liquid) carries its heat through the fluid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] All convective processes also move heat partly by diffusion, as well.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The flow of fluid may be forced by external processes, or sometimes (in gravitational fields) by buoyancy forces caused when thermal energy expands the fluid (for example in a fire plume), thus influencing its own transfer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The latter process is often called "natural convection".
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The former process is often called "forced convection." In this case, the fluid is forced to flow by use of a pump, fan, or other mechanical means.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Thermal radiation occurs through a vacuum or any transparent medium (solid or fluid or gas).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] It is the transfer of energy by means of photons or electromagnetic waves governed by the same laws.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat transfer is the energy exchanged between materials (solid/liquid/gas) as a result of a temperature difference.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The thermodynamic free energy is the amount of work that a thermodynamic system can perform.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Enthalpy is a thermodynamic potential, designated by the letter "H", that is the sum of the internal energy of the system (U) plus the product of pressure (P) and volume (V).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Joule is a unit to quantify energy, work, or the amount of heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Thermodynamic and mechanical heat transfer is calculated with the heat transfer coefficient, the proportionality between the heat flux and the thermodynamic driving force for the flow of heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat flux is a quantitative, vectorial representation of heat flow through a surface.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In engineering contexts, the term *heat* is taken as synonymous with thermal energy.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] This usage has its origin in the historical interpretation of heat as a fluid (*caloric*) that can be transferred by various causes, and that is also common in the language of laymen and everyday life.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Thermal engineering concerns the generation, use, conversion, storage, and exchange of heat transfer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] As such, heat transfer is involved in almost every sector of the economy.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat transfer is classified into various mechanisms, such as thermal conduction, thermal convection, thermal radiation, and transfer of energy by phase changes.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The transfer of energy between objects that are in physical contact.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The transfer of energy between an object and its environment, due to fluid motion.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The average temperature is a reference for evaluating properties related to convective heat transfer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] By transferring matter, energy—including thermal energy—is moved by the physical transfer of a hot or cold object from one place to another.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] This can be as simple as placing hot water in a bottle and heating a bed, or the movement of an iceberg in changing ocean currents.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] A practical example is thermal hydraulics.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] On a microscopic scale, heat conduction occurs as hot, rapidly moving or vibrating atoms and molecules interact with neighboring atoms and molecules, transferring some of their energy (heat) to these neighboring particles.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In other words, heat is transferred by conduction when adjacent atoms vibrate against one another, or as electrons move from one atom to another.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Conduction is the most significant means of heat transfer within a solid or between solid objects in thermal contact.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Fluids—especially gases—are less conductive.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Thermal contact conductance is the study of heat conduction between solid bodies in contact.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Steady-state conduction is an idealized model of conduction that happens when the temperature difference driving the conduction is constant so that after a time, the spatial distribution of temperatures in the conducting object does not change any further (see Fourier's law).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In steady state conduction, the amount of heat entering a section is equal to amount of heat coming out, since the temperature change (a measure of heat energy) is zero.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Another form of convection is forced convection.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In this case, the fluid is forced to flow by using a pump, fan, or other mechanical means.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Convective heat transfer, or simply, convection, is the transfer of heat from one place to another by the movement of fluids, a process that is essentially the transfer of heat via mass transfer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The bulk motion of fluid enhances heat transfer in many physical situations, such as between a solid surface and the fluid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Convection is usually the dominant form of heat transfer in liquids and gases.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Although sometimes discussed as a third method of heat transfer, convection is usually used to describe the combined effects of heat conduction within the fluid (diffusion) and heat transference by bulk fluid flow streaming.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The process of transport by fluid streaming is known as advection, but pure advection is a term that is generally associated only with mass transport in fluids, such as advection of pebbles in a river.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In the case of heat transfer in fluids, where transport by advection in a fluid is always also accompanied by transport via heat diffusion (also known as heat conduction) the process of heat convection is understood to refer to the sum of heat transport by advection and diffusion/conduction.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Free, or natural, convection occurs when bulk fluid motions (streams and currents) are caused by buoyancy forces that result from density variations due to variations of temperature in the fluid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] *Forced* convection is a term used when the streams and currents in the fluid are induced by external means—such as fans, stirrers, and pumps—creating an artificially induced convection current.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] However, by definition, the validity of Newton's law of cooling requires that the rate of heat loss from convection be a linear function of ("proportional to") the temperature difference that drives heat transfer, and in convective cooling this is sometimes not the case.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In general, convection is not linearly dependent on temperature gradients, and in some cases is strongly nonlinear.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In these cases, Newton's law does not apply.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In a body of fluid that is heated from underneath its container, conduction, and convection can be considered to compete for dominance.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] If heat conduction is too great, fluid moving down by convection is heated by conduction so fast that its downward movement will be stopped due to its buoyancy, while fluid moving up by convection is cooled by conduction so fast that its driving buoyancy will diminish.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] On the other hand, if heat conduction is very low, a large temperature gradient may be formed and convection might be very strong.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The Rayleigh number ( $\mathrm {Ra}$ ) is the product of the Grashof ( $\mathrm {Gr}$ ) and Prandtl ( $\mathrm {Pr}$ ) numbers.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] It is a measure that determines the relative strength of conduction and convection.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The Rayleigh number can be understood as the ratio between the rate of heat transfer by convection to the rate of heat transfer by conduction; or, equivalently, the ratio between the corresponding timescales (i.e. conduction timescale divided by convection timescale), up to a numerical factor.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] This can be seen as follows, where all calculations are up to numerical factors depending on the geometry of the system.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The buoyancy force driving the convection is roughly $g\Delta \rho L^{3}$ , so the corresponding pressure is roughly $g\Delta \rho L$ .
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In steady state, this is canceled by the shear stress due to viscosity, and therefore roughly equals $\mu V/L=\mu /T_{\text{conv}}$ , where *V* is the typical fluid velocity due to convection and $T_{\text{conv}}$ the order of its timescale.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The conduction timescale, on the other hand, is of the order of $T_{\text{cond}}=L^{2}/\alpha$ .
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Convection occurs when the Rayleigh number is above 1,000–2,000.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Radiative heat transfer is the transfer of energy via thermal radiation, i.e., electromagnetic waves.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] It occurs across vacuum or any transparent medium (solid or fluid or gas).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Thermal radiation is emitted by all objects at temperatures above absolute zero, due to random movements of atoms and molecules in matter.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Since these atoms and molecules are composed of charged particles (protons and electrons), their movement results in the emission of electromagnetic radiation which carries away energy.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Radiation is typically only important in engineering applications for very hot objects, or for objects with a large temperature difference.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The blackbody limit established by the Stefan-Boltzmann equation can be exceeded when the objects exchanging thermal radiation or the distances separating them are comparable in scale or smaller than the dominant thermal wavelength.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The study of these cases is called near-field radiative heat transfer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Radiation from the sun, or solar radiation, can be harvested for heat and power.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] For example, the sunlight reflected from mirrors heats the PS10 solar power tower and during the day it can heat water to 285 °C (545 °F).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The reachable temperature at the target is limited by the temperature of the hot source of radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] (T4-law lets the reverse flow of radiation back to the source rise.) The (on its surface) somewhat 4000 K hot sun allows to reach coarsely 3000 K (or 3000 °C, which is about 3273 K) at a small probe in the focus spot of a big concave, concentrating mirror of the Mont-Louis Solar Furnace in France.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Phase transition or phase change, takes place in a thermodynamic system from one phase or state of matter to another one by heat transfer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Phase change examples are the melting of ice or the boiling of water.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The Mason equation explains the growth of a water droplet based on the effects of heat transport on evaporation and condensation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The boiling point of a substance is the temperature at which the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the pressure surrounding the liquid and the liquid evaporates resulting in an abrupt change in vapor volume.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In a closed system, *saturation temperature* and *boiling point* mean the same thing.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The saturation temperature is the temperature for a corresponding saturation pressure at which a liquid boils into its vapor phase.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The liquid can be said to be saturated with thermal energy.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Any addition of thermal energy results in a phase transition.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] At standard atmospheric pressure and **low temperatures**, no boiling occurs and the heat transfer rate is controlled by the usual single-phase mechanisms.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] As the surface temperature is increased, local boiling occurs and vapor bubbles nucleate, grow into the surrounding cooler fluid, and collapse.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] This is *sub-cooled nucleate boiling*, and is a very efficient heat transfer mechanism.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] At high bubble generation rates, the bubbles begin to interfere and the heat flux no longer increases rapidly with surface temperature (this is the departure from nucleate boiling, or DNB).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] At similar standard atmospheric pressure and **high temperatures**, the hydrodynamically quieter regime of film boiling is reached.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat fluxes across the stable vapor layers are low but rise slowly with temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Any contact between the fluid and the surface that may be seen probably leads to the extremely rapid nucleation of a fresh vapor layer ("spontaneous nucleation").
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] At higher temperatures still, a maximum in the heat flux is reached (the critical heat flux, or CHF).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The Leidenfrost Effect demonstrates how nucleate boiling slows heat transfer due to gas bubbles on the heater's surface.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] As mentioned, gas-phase thermal conductivity is much lower than liquid-phase thermal conductivity, so the outcome is a kind of "gas thermal barrier".
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Condensation occurs when a vapor is cooled and changes its phase to a liquid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] During condensation, the latent heat of vaporization must be released.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The amount of heat is the same as that absorbed during vaporization at the same fluid pressure.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Melting is a thermal process that results in the phase transition of a substance from a solid to a liquid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The internal energy of a substance is increased, typically through heat or pressure, resulting in a rise of its temperature to the melting point, at which the ordering of ionic or molecular entities in the solid breaks down to a less ordered state and the solid liquefies.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Molten substances generally have reduced viscosity with elevated temperature; an exception to this maxim is the element sulfur, whose viscosity increases to a point due to polymerization and then decreases with higher temperatures in its molten state.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat transfer can be modeled in various ways.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The heat equation is an important partial differential equation that describes the distribution of heat (or temperature variation) in a given region over time.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In some cases, exact solutions of the equation are available; in other cases the equation must be solved numerically using computational methods such as DEM-based models for thermal/reacting particulate systems (as critically reviewed by Peng et al.).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Lumped system analysis often reduces the complexity of the equations to one first-order linear differential equation, in which case heating and cooling are described by a simple exponential solution, often referred to as Newton's law of cooling.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] System analysis by the lumped capacitance model is a common approximation in transient conduction that may be used whenever heat conduction within an object is much faster than heat conduction across the boundary of the object.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] This is a method of approximation that reduces one aspect of the transient conduction system—that within the object—to an equivalent steady-state system.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] That is, the method assumes that the temperature within the object is completely uniform, although its value may change over time.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In this method, the ratio of the conductive heat resistance within the object to the convective heat transfer resistance across the object's boundary, known as the *Biot number*, is calculated.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Climate models study the radiant heat transfer by using quantitative methods to simulate the interactions of the atmosphere, oceans, land surface, and ice.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat transfer has broad application to the functioning of numerous devices and systems.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat-transfer principles may be used to preserve, increase, or decrease temperature in a wide variety of circumstances.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat transfer methods are used in numerous disciplines, such as automotive engineering, thermal management of electronic devices and systems, climate control, insulation, materials processing, chemical engineering and power station engineering.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Thermal insulators are materials specifically designed to reduce the flow of heat by limiting conduction, convection, or both.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Thermal resistance is a heat property and the measurement by which an object or material resists to heat flow (heat per time unit or thermal resistance) to temperature difference.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Radiance, or spectral radiance, is a measure of the quantity of radiation that passes through or is emitted.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Radiant barriers are materials that reflect radiation, and therefore reduce the flow of heat from radiation sources.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Good insulators are not necessarily good radiant barriers, and vice versa.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Metal, for instance, is an excellent reflector and a poor insulator.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The effectiveness of a radiant barrier is indicated by its **reflectivity**, which is the fraction of radiation reflected.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] A material with a high reflectivity (at a given wavelength) has a low emissivity (at that same wavelength), and vice versa.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] At any specific wavelength, reflectivity=1 - emissivity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] An ideal radiant barrier would have a reflectivity of 1, and would therefore reflect 100 percent of incoming radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Vacuum flasks, or Dewars, are silvered to approach this ideal.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In the vacuum of space, satellites use multi-layer insulation, which consists of many layers of aluminized (shiny) Mylar to greatly reduce radiation heat transfer and control satellite temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] A heat engine is a system that performs the conversion of a flow of thermal energy (heat) to mechanical energy to perform mechanical work.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] A thermocouple is a temperature-measuring device and a widely used type of temperature sensor for measurement and control, and can also be used to convert heat into electric power.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] A thermoelectric cooler is a solid-state electronic device that pumps (transfers) heat from one side of the device to the other when an electric current is passed through it.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] A thermal diode or thermal rectifier is a device that causes heat to flow preferentially in one direction.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] A heat exchanger is used for more efficient heat transfer or to dissipate heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat exchangers are widely used in refrigeration, air conditioning, space heating, power generation, and chemical processing.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] One common example of a heat exchanger is a car's radiator, in which the hot coolant fluid is cooled by the flow of air over the radiator's surface.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Common types of heat exchanger flows include parallel flow, counter flow, and cross flow.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In parallel flow, both fluids move in the same direction while transferring heat; in counter flow, the fluids move in opposite directions; and in cross flow, the fluids move at right angles to each other.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Common types of heat exchangers include shell and tube, double pipe, extruded finned pipe, spiral fin pipe, u-tube, and stacked plate.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Each type has certain advantages and disadvantages over other types.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] A heat sink is a component that transfers heat generated within a solid material to a fluid medium, such as air or a liquid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Examples of heat sinks are the heat exchangers used in refrigeration and air conditioning systems or the radiator in a car.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] A heat pipe is another heat-transfer device that combines thermal conductivity and phase transition to efficiently transfer heat between two solid interfaces.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Efficient energy use is the goal to reduce the amount of energy required in heating or cooling.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In architecture, condensation and air currents can cause cosmetic or structural damage.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] An energy audit can help to assess the implementation of recommended corrective procedures.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] For instance, insulation improvements, air sealing of structural leaks, or the addition of energy-efficient windows and doors.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Climate engineering consists of carbon dioxide removal and solar radiation management.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Since the amount of carbon dioxide determines the radiative balance of Earth's atmosphere, carbon dioxide removal techniques can be applied to reduce the radiative forcing.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Solar radiation management is the attempt to absorb less solar radiation to offset the effects of greenhouse gases.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] An alternative method is passive daytime radiative cooling, which enhances terrestrial heat flow to outer space through the infrared window (8–13 μm).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Rather than merely blocking solar radiation, this method increases outgoing longwave infrared (LWIR) thermal radiation heat transfer with the extremely cold temperature of outer space (~2.7 K) to lower ambient temperatures while requiring zero energy input.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] This reduction in outgoing radiation leads to a rise in the temperature of the surface and troposphere until the rate of outgoing radiation again equals the rate at which heat arrives from the Sun.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The principles of heat transfer in engineering systems can be applied to the human body to determine how the body transfers heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat is produced in the body by the continuous metabolism of nutrients which provides energy for the systems of the body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The human body must maintain a consistent internal temperature to maintain healthy bodily functions.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Therefore, excess heat must be dissipated from the body to keep it from overheating.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] When a person engages in elevated levels of physical activity, the body requires additional fuel which increases the metabolic rate and the rate of heat production.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The body must then use additional methods to remove the additional heat produced to keep the internal temperature at a healthy level.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat transfer by convection is driven by the movement of fluids over the surface of the body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] This convective fluid can be either a liquid or a gas.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] For heat transfer from the outer surface of the body, the convection mechanism is dependent on the surface area of the body, the velocity of the air, and the temperature gradient between the surface of the skin and the ambient air.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The normal temperature of the body is approximately 37 °C.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Heat transfer occurs more readily when the temperature of the surroundings is significantly less than the normal body temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] This concept explains why a person feels cold when not enough covering is worn when exposed to a cold environment.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Clothing can be considered an insulator which provides thermal resistance to heat flow over the covered portion of the body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] This thermal resistance causes the temperature on the surface of the clothing to be less than the temperature on the surface of the skin.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] This smaller temperature gradient between the surface temperature and the ambient temperature will cause a lower rate of heat transfer than if the skin were not covered.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] To ensure that one portion of the body is not significantly hotter than another portion, heat must be distributed evenly through the bodily tissues.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Blood flowing through blood vessels acts as a convective fluid and helps to prevent any buildup of excess heat inside the tissues of the body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] This flow of blood through the vessels can be modeled as pipe flow in an engineering system.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The heat carried by the blood is determined by the temperature of the surrounding tissue, the diameter of the blood vessel, the thickness of the fluid, the velocity of the flow, and the heat transfer coefficient of the blood.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The velocity, blood vessel diameter, and fluid thickness can all be related to the Reynolds Number, a dimensionless number used in fluid mechanics to characterize the flow of fluids.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Latent heat loss, also known as evaporative heat loss, accounts for a large fraction of heat loss from the body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] When the core temperature of the body increases, the body triggers sweat glands in the skin to bring additional moisture to the surface of the skin.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The liquid is then transformed into vapor which removes heat from the surface of the body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The rate of evaporation heat loss is directly related to the vapor pressure at the skin surface and the amount of moisture present on the skin.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Therefore, the maximum of heat transfer will occur when the skin is completely wet.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The body continuously loses water by evaporation but the most significant amount of heat loss occurs during periods of increased physical activity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Evaporative cooling happens when water vapor is added to the surrounding air.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The energy needed to evaporate the water is taken from the air in the form of sensible heat and converted into latent heat, while the air remains at a constant enthalpy.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Latent heat describes the amount of heat that is needed to evaporate the liquid; this heat comes from the liquid itself and the surrounding gas and surfaces.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The greater the difference between the two temperatures, the greater the evaporative cooling effect.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] When the temperatures are the same, no net evaporation of water in the air occurs; thus, there is no cooling effect.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In quantum physics, laser cooling is used to achieve temperatures of near absolute zero (−273.15 °C, −459.67 °F) of atomic and molecular samples to observe unique quantum effects that can only occur at this heat level.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Magnetic evaporative cooling is a process for lowering the temperature of a group of atoms, after pre-cooled by methods such as laser cooling.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Magnetic refrigeration cools below 0.3K, by making use of the magnetocaloric effect.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Radiative cooling is the process by which a body loses heat by radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Outgoing energy is an important effect in the Earth's energy budget.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In the case of the Earth-atmosphere system, it refers to the process by which long-wave (infrared) radiation is emitted to balance the absorption of short-wave (visible) energy from the Sun.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The thermosphere (top of atmosphere) cools to space primarily by infrared energy radiated by carbon dioxide (CO2) at 15 μm and by nitric oxide (NO) at 5.3 μm.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Convective transport of heat and evaporative transport of latent heat both remove heat from the surface and redistribute it in the atmosphere.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Thermal energy storage includes technologies for collecting and storing energy for later use.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] It may be employed to balance energy demand between day and nighttime.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The thermal reservoir may be maintained at a temperature above or below that of the ambient environment.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Applications include space heating, domestic or process hot water systems, or generating electricity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In 1701, Isaac Newton anonymously published an article in *Philosophical Transactions* noting (in modern terms) that the rate of temperature change of a body is proportional to the difference in temperatures (*graduum caloris*, "degrees of heat") between the body and its surroundings.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The phrase "temperature change" was later replaced with "heat loss", and the relationship was named Newton's law of cooling.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In general, the law is valid only if the temperature difference is small and the heat transfer mechanism remains the same.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In heat conduction, the law is valid only if the thermal conductivity of the warmer body is independent of temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The thermal conductivity of most materials is only weakly dependent on temperature, so in general the law holds true.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In convective heat transfer, the law is valid for forced air or pumped fluid cooling, where the properties of the fluid do not vary strongly with temperature, but it is only approximately true for buoyancy-driven convection, where the velocity of the flow increases with temperature difference.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In the case of heat transfer by thermal radiation, Newton's law of cooling holds only for very small temperature differences.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] During the years 1784 – 1798, the British physicist Benjamin Thompson (Count Rumford) lived in Bavaria, reorganizing the Bavarian army for the Prince-elector Charles Theodore among other official and charitable duties.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The Elector gave Thompson access to the facilities of the Electoral Academy of Sciences in Mannheim.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] During his years in Mannheim and later in Munich, Thompson made a large number of discoveries and inventions related to heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] In 1785 Thompson performed a series of thermal conductivity experiments, which he describes in great detail in the *Philosophical Transactions* article "New Experiments upon Heat" from 1786.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] The fact that good electrical conductors are often also good heat conductors and vice versa must have been well known at the time, for Thompson mentions it in passing.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] He intended to measure the relative conductivities of mercury, water, moist air, "common air" (dry air at normal atmospheric pressure), dry air of various rarefication, and a "Torricellian vacuum".
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] For these experiments, Thompson employed a thermometer inside a large, closed glass tube.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Under the circumstances described, heat may—unbeknownst to Thompson—have been transferred more by radiation than by conduction.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] After the experiments, Thompson was surprised to observe that a vacuum was a significantly poorer heat conductor than air "which of itself is reckoned among the worst", but only a very small difference between common air and rarefied air.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] He also noted the great difference between dry air and moist air, and the great benefit this affords.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/heat-transfer] Thompson concluded with some comments on the important difference between temperature and sensible heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The **Nusselt number** is a nondimensionalization of the convective heat transfer coefficient.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] Like the heat transfer coefficient, the Nusselt number may be defined locally, at a single position on a surface, or as an average value that represents the heat flow from the entire surface.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The Nusselt number is named in honor of Wilhelm Nusselt, who first identified this dimensionless group in 1915.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] Analytical results and empirical correlations allow the Nusselt number to be estimated in many situations.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] For forced convection, these expressions depend on the Reynolds number and the Prandtl number.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] For natural convection (or "free" convection) the predictions use the Grashof number or Rayleigh number along with the Prandtl number.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The mass transfer analog of the Nusselt number is the Sherwood number.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The group now known as the Nusselt number was first identified by Wilhelm Nusselt in a 1915 paper.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] In that paper, he also identified the groups that became the Grashof number, the Prandtl number, and the Reynolds number.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] Nusselt used these groups effectively to correlate data for natural convection and, in a 1917 paper, forced convection.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] In 1931, the Association of German Engineers formally named the dimensionless group the *Nusselt number*.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The decision was announced in paper by Max Jakob.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The term was quickly adopted internationally.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The heat transfer coefficient, h , at a surface cooled by a fluid is the ratio of the heat flux q [W/m2] from the surface to the temperature difference $\Delta T$ [K] between the surface and the fluid far from the surface: $h=q/\Delta T$ [W/(m2·K)].
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The Nusselt number is a dimensionless group.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The subscript, *L*, indicates which characteristic length is used.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The characteristic length should be related to the thickness of the thermal boundary layer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] In a tube, the thermal boundary layer will be limited by the tube diameter, D , so that the diameter represents the scale of the boundary layer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] On a flat plate, the length of the plate, L , determines the average thickness of the boundary layer on the plate.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] On the other hand, the local thickness of the flat plate boundary layer, at a position x , is determined by the value of x , so that x is the characteristic length for the local heat transfer coefficient on the plate.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] Some additional examples of characteristic length are: the outer diameter of a cylinder in (external) crossflow (perpendicular to the cylinder axis), the height of a vertical plate undergoing natural convection, or the diameter of a sphere.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] For complex shapes, the length may be defined as the volume of the fluid body divided by the surface area.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The local heat transfer coefficient varies along the surface of a body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] It becomes lower as the thermal boundary layer becomes thicker.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] It increases suddenly where the boundary layer transitions from laminar to turbulent flow.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The average heat transfer coefficient relates the average temperature difference to the average heat flux over the body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The term "average Nusselt number" can cause confusion because the Nusselt number is not what has been averaged.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] For an isothermal surface, the heat flux has been averaged, while for a uniform flux surface, the temperature difference has been averaged.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] where $\rho ,c_{p},{\text{and }}u$ are the fluid density, specific heat capacity, and free stream speed.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] A similar nondimensional group is the Biot number, which compares the thermal resistance of heat conduction in the body to the thermal resistance of convection outside the body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The Biot number uses the thermal conductivity of the solid body rather than the fluid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The Biot number should not be confused with the Nusselt number.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] An understanding of convection boundary layers is necessary to understand convective heat transfer between a surface and a fluid flowing past it.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] A thermal boundary layer develops if the fluid free stream temperature and the surface temperatures differ.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] A temperature profile is created by the energy exchange resulting from this temperature difference.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] Analytical results and empirical correlations that express the Nusselt number in the aforementioned forms are available for a wide variety of geometries.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] When calculating the Nusselt number, the thermal conductivity, the Prandtl number, and the properties in the Reynolds or Grashof numbers are usually evaluated at the film temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The film temperature is the average of the wall temperature and free stream or bulk temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] When the bulk temperature changes significantly along the length of the tube, the average bulk temperature can be used.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The transition from a laminar to a turbulent boundary occurs at $\mathrm {Ra} _{L}\approx 10^{9}$ .
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] where $\mathrm {A} _{s}$ is the surface area of the plate and P is its perimeter.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The solution of the energy and momentum equations for laminar flow over an isothermal flat plate leads to the following equation for the local Nusselt number at a distance x downstream from the leading edge of the plate.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The result limits to $\mathrm {Nu} _{D}\ ={2}$ for small Reynolds numbers, which corresponds to heat conduction into a sphere in an infinite medium.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] This correlation is much more accurate than 1930s power-law correlations such as the Dittus–Boelter equation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] Gnielinski also developed power-law correlations for limited ranges of Prandtl number, which agree very closely with his full-range correlation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] These equations apply for smooth tubes with $3000\leq \mathrm {Re} _{D}\leq 5\times 10^{6}$ .
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The Dittus–Boelter equation (for turbulent flow in smooth-walled tubes), as introduced by W.H.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] McAdams, is one of several power-law correlations that were published in the 1930s.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] These equations are based on smaller data sets than the Gnielinski correlations, represent smaller ranges of Reynolds and Prandtl number, and are generally less accurate.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The Sieder–Tate correlation for turbulent pipe flow (1936) takes account of the change in viscosity ( $\mu _{b}$ and $\mu _{w}$ ) due to temperature change between the average bulk temperature of the fluid and wall temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] The Sieder–Tate correlation may need to be solved iteratively if the bulk or wall temperature is unknown.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] Taking water with a bulk fluid average temperature of 20 °C (68 °F), viscosity 10.07×10−4 Pa.s and a heat transfer surface temperature of 40 °C (104 °F) (viscosity 6.96×10−4 Pa.s, a viscosity correction factor for $({\mu }/{\mu _{s}})$ can be obtained as 1.45.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] This increases to 3.57 with a heat transfer surface temperature of 100 °C (212 °F) (viscosity 2.82×10−4 Pa.s), making a significant difference to the Nusselt number and the heat transfer coefficient.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/nusselt-number] Solution of the governing equations for fully developed, laminar pipe flow leads to very simple results.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] A hotter region experiences greater molecular agitation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] When a hotter object touches a cooler surface, the molecules from the hot object bump the molecules of the cooler surface, transferring kinetic energy, heating the colder object.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Mathematically, thermal conduction works via diffusion.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Conduction is the main mode of heat transfer for solid materials because the strong inter-molecular forces allow the vibrations of particles to be easily transmitted, in comparison to liquids and gases.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Liquids have weaker inter-molecular forces and more space between the particles, which makes the vibrations of particles harder to transmit.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Gases have even more space, and therefore infrequent particle collisions.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This makes liquids and gases poor conductors of heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Thermal contact conductance is heat conduction between solid bodies in contact.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] A temperature drop is often observed at the interface between the two surfaces.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This phenomenon is a result of a thermal contact resistance between the contacting surfaces.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Interfacial thermal resistance is an interface's resistance to thermal flow.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This resistance differs from contact resistance, as it exists even at atomically perfect interfaces.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Understanding the thermal resistance at the interface between two materials is of primary significance in the study of thermal properties.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Interfaces often contribute significantly to the observed properties of the materials.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Inter-molecular energy transfer could be primarily by elastic impact, as in fluids, or by free-electron diffusion, as in metals, or phonon vibration, as in insulators.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In insulators, the heat flux is carried almost entirely by phonon vibrations.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Metals (e.g., copper, platinum, gold, etc.) are typically good conductors.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This is due to the way that metals bond chemically: metallic bonds (as opposed to covalent or ionic bonds) have free-moving electrons that transfer thermal energy rapidly.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The electron fluid of a conductive metallic solid conducts heat flux through the solid.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Phonon flux is present, but carries less energy.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Electrons conduct electric current through conductive solids, and the thermal and electrical conductivities of most metals have about the same ratio.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] A good electrical conductor, such as copper, conducts heat well.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Thermoelectricity is caused by the interaction of heat flux and electric current.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Heat conduction within a solid is directly analogous to diffusion of particles within a fluid, absent fluid currents.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In gases, heat transfer occurs through collisions of gas molecules.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Without convection, which relates to a fluid or gas phase, thermal conduction through a gas phase is dependent on the composition and pressure of this phase, and in particular, the mean free path of gas molecules relative to the size of the gas gap, as given by the Knudsen number $K_{n}$ .
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] To quantify the ease with which a particular medium conducts, engineers measure thermal conductivity, also known as the conductivity constant or conduction coefficient, *k*.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In thermal conductivity, *k* is defined as "the quantity of heat, *Q*, transmitted in time (*t*) through a thickness (*L*), in a direction normal to a surface of area (*A*), due to a temperature difference (Δ*T*) [...]".
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Thermal conductivity is a material property that is primarily dependent on the medium's phase, temperature, density, and molecular bonding.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Thermal effusivity is derived from conductivity, which is a measure of its ability to exchange thermal energy with its surroundings.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Steady-state conduction is the form of conduction that happens when the temperature difference(s) driving the conduction are constant, so that (after an equilibration time), the spatial distribution of temperatures (temperature field) in the conducting object does not change any further.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Thus, all partial derivatives of temperature *concerning space* may either be zero or have nonzero values, but all derivatives of temperature at any point *concerning time* are uniformly zero.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In steady-state conduction, the amount of heat entering any region of an object is equal to the amount of heat coming out (if this were not so, the temperature would be rising or falling, as thermal energy was tapped or trapped in a region).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] For example, a bar may be cold at one end and hot at the other, but after a state of steady-state conduction is reached, the spatial gradient of temperatures along the bar does not change any further, as time proceeds.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Instead, the temperature remains constant at any given cross-section of the rod normal to the direction of heat transfer, and this temperature varies linearly in space in the case where there is no heat generation in the rod.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In steady-state conduction, all the laws of direct current electrical conduction can be applied to "heat currents".
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In such cases, it is possible to take "thermal resistances" as the analog to electrical resistances.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In such cases, temperature plays the role of voltage, and heat transferred per unit time (heat power) is the analog of electric current.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Steady-state systems can be modeled by networks of such thermal resistances in series and parallel, in exact analogy to electrical networks of resistors.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] See purely resistive thermal circuits for an example of such a network.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] During any period in which temperatures changes *in time* at any place within an object, the mode of thermal energy flow is termed *transient conduction.* Another term is "non-steady-state" conduction, referring to the time-dependence of temperature fields in an object.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Non-steady-state situations appear after an imposed change in temperature at a boundary of an object.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] They may also occur with temperature changes inside an object, as a result of a new source or sink of heat suddenly introduced within an object, causing temperatures near the source or sink to change in time.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] When a new perturbation of temperature of this type happens, temperatures within the system change in time toward a new equilibrium with the new conditions, provided that these do not change.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] After equilibrium, heat flow into the system once again equals the heat flow out, and temperatures at each point inside the system no longer change.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Once this happens, transient conduction is ended, although steady-state conduction may continue if heat flow continues.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] If changes in external temperatures or internal heat generation changes are too rapid for the equilibrium of temperatures in space to take place, then the system never reaches a state of unchanging temperature distribution in time, and the system remains in a transient state.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] An example of a new source of heat "turning on" within an object, causing transient conduction, is an engine starting in an automobile.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In this case, the transient thermal conduction phase for the entire machine is over, and the steady-state phase appears, as soon as the engine reaches steady-state operating temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In this state of steady-state equilibrium, temperatures vary greatly from the engine cylinders to other parts of the automobile, but at no point in space within the automobile does temperature increase or decrease.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] After establishing this state, the transient conduction phase of heat transfer is over.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] New external conditions also cause this process: for example, the copper bar in the example steady-state conduction experiences transient conduction as soon as one end is subjected to a different temperature from the other.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Over time, the field of temperatures inside the bar reaches a new steady-state, in which a constant temperature gradient along the bar is finally set up, and this gradient then stays constant in time.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Typically, such a new steady-state gradient is approached exponentially with time after a new temperature-or-heat source or sink, has been introduced.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] When a "transient conduction" phase is over, heat flow may continue at high power, so long as temperatures do not change.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] An example of transient conduction that does not end with steady-state conduction, but rather no conduction, occurs when a hot copper ball is dropped into oil at a low temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Mathematically, this condition is also approached exponentially; in theory, it takes infinite time, but in practice, it is over, for all intents and purposes, in a much shorter period.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] At the end of this process with no heat sink but the internal parts of the ball (which are finite), there is no steady-state heat conduction to reach.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Such a state never occurs in this situation, but rather the end of the process is when there is no heat conduction at all.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The analysis of non-steady-state conduction systems is more complex than that of steady-state systems.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] If the conducting body has a simple shape, then exact analytical mathematical expressions and solutions may be possible (see heat equation for the analytical approach).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] However, most often, because of complicated shapes with varying thermal conductivities within the shape (i.e., most complex objects, mechanisms or machines in engineering) often the application of approximate theories is required, and/or numerical analysis by computer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] One popular graphical method involves the use of Heisler Charts.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Occasionally, transient conduction problems may be considerably simplified if regions of the object being heated or cooled can be identified, for which thermal conductivity is very much greater than that for heat paths leading into the region.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In this case, the region with high conductivity can often be treated in the lumped capacitance model, as a "lump" of material with a simple thermal capacitance consisting of its aggregate heat capacity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Such regions warm or cool, but show no significant temperature *variation* across their extent, during the process (as compared to the rest of the system).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This is due to their far higher conductance.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] During transient conduction, therefore, the temperature across their conductive regions changes uniformly in space, and as a simple exponential in time.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] An example of such systems is those that follow Newton's law of cooling during transient cooling (or the reverse during heating).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The equivalent thermal circuit consists of a simple capacitor in series with a resistor.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In such cases, the remainder of the system with a high thermal resistance (comparatively low conductivity) plays the role of the resistor in the circuit.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The theory of relativistic heat conduction is a model that is compatible with the theory of special relativity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] For most of the last century, it was recognized that the Fourier equation is in contradiction with the theory of relativity because it admits an infinite speed of propagation of heat signals.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] For example, according to the Fourier equation, a pulse of heat at the origin would be felt at infinity instantaneously.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The speed of information propagation is faster than the speed of light in vacuum, which is physically inadmissible within the framework of relativity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Second sound is a quantum mechanical phenomenon in which heat transfer occurs by wave-like motion, rather than by the more usual mechanism of diffusion.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Heat takes the place of pressure in normal sound waves.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This leads to a very high thermal conductivity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] It is known as "second sound" because the wave motion of heat is similar to the propagation of sound in air.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The law of heat conduction, also known as Fourier's law (compare Fourier's heat equation), states that the rate of heat transfer through a material is proportional to the negative gradient in the temperature and to the area, at right angles to that gradient, through which the heat flows.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] We can state this law in two equivalent forms: the integral form, in which we look at the amount of energy flowing into or out of a body as a whole, and the differential form, in which we look at the flow rates or fluxes of energy locally.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Newton's law of cooling is a discrete analogue of Fourier's law, while Ohm's law is the electrical analogue of Fourier's law and Fick's laws of diffusion is its chemical analogue.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The differential form of Fourier's law of thermal conduction shows that the local heat flux density $\mathbf {q}$ is equal to the product of thermal conductivity $\kappa$ and the negative local temperature gradient $-\nabla T$ .
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The thermal conductivity k is often treated as a constant, though this is not always true.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] While the thermal conductivity of a material generally varies with temperature, the variation can be small over a significant range of temperatures for some common materials.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In anisotropic materials, the thermal conductivity typically varies with orientation; in this case $\kappa$ is represented by a second-order tensor.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In non-uniform materials, $\kappa$ varies with spatial location.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This law forms the basis for the derivation of the heat equation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Writing $U={\frac {k}{\Delta x}},$ where U is the conductance, in W/(m2 K).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Resistance is additive when several conducting layers lie between the hot and cool regions, because *A* and *Q* are the same for all layers.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] For heat conduction from one fluid to another through a barrier, it is sometimes important to consider the conductance of the thin film of fluid that remains stationary next to the barrier.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This thin film of fluid is difficult to quantify because its characteristics depend upon complex conditions of turbulence and viscosity—but when dealing with thin high-conductance barriers it can sometimes be quite significant.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The previous conductance equations, written in terms of extensive properties, can be reformulated in terms of intensive properties.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Ideally, the formulae for conductance should produce a quantity with dimensions independent of distance, like Ohm's law for electrical resistance, $R=V/I\,\!$ , and conductance, $G=I/V\,\!$ .
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] From the electrical formula: $R=\rho x/A$ , where *ρ* is resistivity, *x* is length, and *A* is cross-sectional area, we have $G=kA/x\,\!$ , where *G* is conductance, *k* is conductivity, *x* is length, and *A* is cross-sectional area.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] For heat, $U={\frac {kA}{\Delta x}},$ where U is the conductance.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The rules for combining resistances and conductances (in series and parallel) are the same for both heat flow and electric current.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Conduction through cylindrical shells (e.g. pipes) can be calculated from the internal radius, $r_{1}$ , the external radius, $r_{2}$ , the length, $\ell$ , and the temperature difference between the inner and outer wall, $T_{2}-T_{1}$ .
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The conduction through a spherical shell with internal radius, $r_{1}$ , and external radius, $r_{2}$ , can be calculated in a similar manner as for a cylindrical shell.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The heat transfer at an interface is considered a transient heat flow.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] To analyze this problem, the Biot number is important to understand how the system behaves.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The Biot number is determined by: ${\text{Bi}}={\frac {hL}{k}}$ The heat transfer coefficient h , is introduced in this formula, and is measured in $\mathrm {\frac {J}{m^{2}sK}}$ .
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] If the system has a Biot number of less than 0.1, the material behaves according to Newtonian cooling, i.e. with negligible temperature gradient within the body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] If the Biot number is greater than 0.1, the system behaves as a series solution. however, there is a noticeable temperature gradient within the material, and a series solution is required to describe the temperature profile.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The heat transfer coefficient, *h*, is measured in $\mathrm {\frac {W}{m^{2}K}}$ , and represents the transfer of heat at an interface between two materials.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This value is different at every interface and is an important concept in understanding heat flow at an interface.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The series solution can be analyzed with a nomogram.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The Biot number increases as the Fourier number decreases.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] There are five steps to determine a temperature profile in terms of time.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Determine which relative depth matters, either *x* or *L*.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Convert $T_{i}$ to relative temperature with the boundary conditions.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Compared required to point to trace specified Biot number on the nomogram.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Splat cooling is a method for quenching small droplets of molten materials by rapid contact with a cold surface.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The particles undergo a characteristic cooling process, with the heat profile at $t=0$ for initial temperature as the maximum at $x=0$ and $T=0$ at $x=-\infty$ and $x=\infty$ , and the heat profile at $t=\infty$ for $-\infty \leq x\leq \infty$ as the boundary conditions.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Splat cooling rapidly ends in a steady state temperature, and is similar in form to the Gaussian diffusion equation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Splat cooling is a fundamental concept that has been adapted for practical use in the form of thermal spraying.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The thermal diffusivity coefficient, represented as $\alpha$ , can be written as $\alpha ={\frac {k}{\rho C_{p}}}$ .
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Metal quenching is a transient heat transfer process in terms of the time temperature transformation (TTT).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] It is possible to manipulate the cooling process to adjust the phase of a suitable material.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] For example, appropriate quenching of steel can convert a desirable proportion of its content of austenite to martensite, creating a very hard and strong product.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] To achieve this, it is necessary to quench at the "nose" (or eutectic) of the TTT diagram.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Since materials differ in their Biot numbers, the time it takes for the material to quench, or the Fourier number, varies in practice.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In steel, the quenching temperature range is generally from 600 °C to 200 °C.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] To control the quenching time and to select suitable quenching media, it is necessary to determine the Fourier number from the desired quenching time, the relative temperature drop, and the relevant Biot number.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Usually, the correct figures are read from a standard nomogram.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] By calculating the heat transfer coefficient from this Biot number, one can find a liquid medium suitable for the application.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] One statement of the so-called zeroth law of thermodynamics is directly focused on the idea of conduction of heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Bailyn (1994) writes that "the zeroth law may be stated: All diathermal walls are equivalent".
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] A diathermal wall is a physical connection between two bodies that allows the passage of heat between them.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Bailyn is referring to diathermal walls that exclusively connect two bodies, especially conductive walls.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This statement of the "zeroth law" belongs to an idealized theoretical discourse, and actual physical walls may have peculiarities that do not conform to its generality.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] For example, the material of the wall must not undergo a phase transition, such as evaporation or fusion, at the temperature at which it must conduct heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] But when only thermal equilibrium is considered and time is not urgent, so that the conductivity of the material does not matter too much, one suitable heat conductor is as good as another.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Conversely, another aspect of the zeroth law is that, subject again to suitable restrictions, a given diathermal wall is indifferent to the nature of the heat bath to which it is connected.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] For example, the glass bulb of a thermometer acts as a diathermal wall whether exposed to a gas or a liquid, provided that they do not corrode or melt it.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] These differences are among the defining characteristics of heat transfer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] In a sense, they are symmetries of heat transfer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Thermal conduction property of any gas under standard conditions of pressure and temperature is a fixed quantity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This property of a known reference gas or known reference gas mixtures can, therefore, be used for certain sensory applications, such as the thermal conductivity analyzer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The working of this instrument is by principle based on the Wheatstone bridge containing four filaments whose resistances are matched.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Whenever a certain gas is passed over such network of filaments, their resistance changes due to the altered thermal conductivity of the filaments and thereby changing the net voltage output from the Wheatstone Bridge.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] This voltage output will be correlated with the database to identify the gas sample.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The principle of thermal conductivity of gases can also be used to measure the concentration of a gas in a binary mixture of gases.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Working: if the same gas is present around all the Wheatstone bridge filaments, then the same temperature is maintained in all the filaments and hence same resistances are also maintained; resulting in a balanced Wheatstone bridge.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] However, If the dissimilar gas sample (or gas mixture) is passed over one set of two filaments and the reference gas on the other set of two filaments, then the Wheatstone bridge becomes unbalanced.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] And the resulting net voltage output of the circuit will be correlated with the database to identify the constituents of the sample gas.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] Using this technique many unknown gas samples can be identified by comparing their thermal conductivity with other reference gas of known thermal conductivity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-conduction] The most commonly used reference gas is nitrogen; as the thermal conductivity of most common gases (except hydrogen and helium) are similar to that of nitrogen.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Kinetic energy is converted to electromagnetism due to charge-acceleration or dipole oscillation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] At room temperature, most of the emission is in the infrared (IR) spectrum, though above around 525 °C (977 °F) enough of it becomes visible for the matter to visibly glow.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] This visible glow is called **incandescence**.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermal radiation is one of the fundamental mechanisms of heat transfer, along with conduction and convection.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The primary method by which the Sun transfers heat to the Earth is thermal radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] This energy is partially absorbed and scattered in the atmosphere, the latter process being the reason why the sky is visibly blue.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Much of the Sun's radiation transmits through the atmosphere to the surface where it is either absorbed or reflected.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermal radiation can be used to detect objects or phenomena normally invisible to the human eye.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermographic cameras create an image by sensing infrared radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] These images can represent the temperature gradient of a scene and are commonly used to locate objects at a higher temperature than their surroundings.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In a dark environment where visible light is at low levels, infrared images can be used to locate animals or people due to their body temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Cosmic microwave background radiation is another example of thermal radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Black-body radiation is a concept used to analyze thermal radiation in idealized systems.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] This model applies if a radiating object meets the physical characteristics of a black body in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Planck's law describes the spectrum of black-body radiation, and relates the radiative heat flux from a body to its temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Wien's displacement law determines the most likely frequency of the emitted radiation, and the Stefan–Boltzmann law gives the radiant intensity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Where black-body radiation is not an accurate approximation, emission and absorption can be modeled using quantum electrodynamics (QED).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermal radiation is the emission of electromagnetic waves from all matter that has a temperature greater than absolute zero.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermal radiation reflects the conversion of thermal energy into electromagnetic energy.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermal energy is the kinetic energy of random movements of atoms and molecules in matter.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] It is present in all matter of nonzero temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] These atoms and molecules are composed of charged particles, i.e., protons and electrons.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The kinetic interactions among matter particles result in charge acceleration and dipole oscillation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] This results in the electrodynamic generation of coupled electric and magnetic fields, resulting in the emission of photons, radiating energy away from the body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Electromagnetic radiation, including visible light, will propagate indefinitely in vacuum.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The characteristics of thermal radiation depend on various properties of the surface from which it is emanating, including its temperature and its spectral emissivity, as expressed by Kirchhoff's law.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The radiation is not monochromatic, i.e., it does not consist of only a single frequency, but comprises a continuous spectrum of photon energies, its characteristic spectrum.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] If the radiating body and its surface are in thermodynamic equilibrium and the surface has perfect absorptivity at all wavelengths, it is characterized as a black body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The radiation of such perfect emitters is called black-body radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The ratio of any body's emission relative to that of a black body is the body's emissivity, so a black body has an emissivity of one.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The absorptivity, emissivity, reflectivity, and transmissivity of all bodies are dependent on the wavelength of the radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Due to reciprocity, absorptivity and emissivity for any particular wavelength are equal at equilibrium – a good absorber is necessarily a good emitter, and a poor absorber is a poor emitter.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The temperature determines the wavelength distribution of the electromagnetic radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The distribution of power that a black body emits with varying frequency is described by Planck's law.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] At any given temperature, there is a frequency *f*max at which the power emitted is a maximum.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Wien's displacement law, and the fact that the frequency is inversely proportional to the wavelength, indicates that the peak frequency *f*max is proportional to the absolute temperature *T* of the black body.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The photosphere of the sun, at a temperature of approximately 6000 K, emits radiation principally in the (human-)visible portion of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Earth's atmosphere is partly transparent to visible light, and the light reaching the surface is absorbed or reflected.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Earth's surface emits the absorbed radiation, approximating the behavior of a black body at 300 K with spectral peak at *f*max.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] At these lower frequencies, the atmosphere is largely opaque and radiation from Earth's surface is absorbed or scattered by the atmosphere.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Though about 10% of this radiation escapes into space, most is absorbed and then re-emitted by atmospheric gases.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] It is this spectral selectivity of the atmosphere that is responsible for the planetary greenhouse effect, contributing to global warming and climate change in general (but also critically contributing to climate stability when the composition and properties of the atmosphere are not changing).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Burning glasses are known to date back to about 700 BC.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] One of the first accurate mentions of burning glasses appears in Aristophanes's comedy *The Clouds*, written in 423 BC.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] According to the Archimedes' heat ray anecdote, Archimedes is purported to have developed mirrors to concentrate heat rays in order to burn attacking Roman ships during the Siege of Syracuse (c.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] 213–212 BC), but no sources from the time have been confirmed.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] *Catoptrics* is a book attributed to Euclid on how to focus light in order to produce heat, but the book might have been written in 300 AD.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] During the Renaissance, Santorio Santorio came up with one of the earliest thermoscopes.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In 1612, he published his results on the heating effects from the Sun and his attempts to measure heat from the Moon.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Earlier, in 1589, Giambattista della Porta reported on the heat felt on his face, emitted by a remote candle and facilitated by a concave metallic mirror.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] He also reported the cooling felt from a solid ice block.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Della Porta's experiment would be replicated many times with increasing accuracy.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] It was replicated by astronomers Giovanni Antonio Magini and Christopher Heydon in 1603, and supplied instructions for Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor who performed it in 1611.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In 1660, della Porta's experiment was updated by the Accademia del Cimento using a thermometer invented by Ferdinand II, Grand Duke of Tuscany.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In 1761, Benjamin Franklin wrote a letter describing his experiments on the relationship between color and heat absorption.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] He found that darker color clothes got hotter when exposed to sunlight than lighter color clothes.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] One experiment he performed consisted of placing square pieces of cloth of various colors out in the snow on a sunny day.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] He waited some time and then measured that the black pieces sank furthest into the snow of all the colors, indicating that they got the hottest and melted the most snow.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Antoine Lavoisier considered that radiation of heat was concerned with the condition of the surface of a physical body rather than the material of which it was composed.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Lavoisier described a poor radiator to be a substance with a polished or smooth surface as it possessed its molecules lying in a plane closely bound together thus creating a surface layer of caloric fluid which insulated the release of the rest within.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] He described a good radiator to be a substance with a rough surface as only a small proportion of molecules held caloric in within a given plane, allowing for greater escape from within.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Count Rumford would later cite this explanation of caloric movement as insufficient to explain the radiation of cold, which became a point of contention for the theory as a whole.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In his first memoir, Augustin-Jean Fresnel responded to a view he extracted from a French translation of Isaac Newton's *Optics*.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] He says that Newton imagined particles of light traversing space uninhibited by the caloric medium filling it, and refutes this view (never actually held by Newton) by saying that a body under illumination would increase indefinitely in heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In Marc-Auguste Pictet's famous experiment of 1790, it was reported that a thermometer detected a lower temperature when a set of mirrors were used to focus "frigorific rays" from a cold object.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In 1791, Pierre Prevost a colleague of Pictet, introduced the concept of radiative equilibrium, wherein all objects both radiate and absorb heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] When an object is cooler than its surroundings, it absorbs more heat than it emits, causing its temperature to increase until it reaches equilibrium.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Even at equilibrium, it continues to radiate heat, balancing absorption and emission.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In the early 19th century, scientist showed that radiant heat had the same properties of light.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] About the same period, light was shown to have a wave nature by Augustin-Jean Fresnel, rejecting the corpuscular theory of light.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The discovery of infrared radiation is ascribed to astronomer William Herschel.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Herschel published his results in 1800 before the Royal Society of London.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Herschel used a prism to refract light from the sun and detected the calorific rays, beyond the red part of the spectrum, by an increase in the temperature recorded on a thermometer in that region.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In 1804, John Leslie experimented with different cubes filled with hot/cold water with different coated sides.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The Leslie cube experiment showed black surfaces emitted more radiation than silvery surfaces.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac wrote in 1920 about the development of the theory of heat propagation in vacuum (French: *calorique du vide*) would require a new theory of heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Between 1830 and 1832, Macedonio Melloni, with the initial help of Leopoldo Nobili, creates a thermomultiplier to carry a series of measurements on radiant heat.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Melloni demonstrate that radiant heat has all the same properties of light including reflection, refraction, diffraction and polarization.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Melloni however did not fully adhere the wave theory of heat until 1847.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] André-Marie Ampère is credited of having written the first treatise on propagation of heat as a wave in 1832, and expanded in 1835.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Ampère did not reject caloric theory entirely but he favored wave theory as more convenient.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The theory however had backlash from the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Despite its success, the wave theory of heat was mostly abandoned by leading scientists since the 1850s with the development of the concept of mechanical equivalent of heat, thermodynamics and the kinetic theory of gases.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In 1860, Gustav Kirchhoff published a mathematical description of thermal equilibrium (i.e.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Kirchhoff's law of thermal radiation).In the late 1870s, the instrument to measure heat radiation, the bolometer, was invented and patented by Samuel Langley.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] By 1884 the emissive power of a perfect blackbody was inferred by Josef Stefan using John Tyndall's experimental measurements, and derived by Ludwig Boltzmann from fundamental statistical principles.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] This relation is known as Stefan–Boltzmann law.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In 1893, Wilhelm Wien empirically developed Wien's displacement law indicating at which wavelength the radiation is most intense at a certain temperature for black-body radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] At the end of the 19th century, it was shown that the transmission of light or of radiant heat was allowed by the propagation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Television and radio broadcasting waves are types of electromagnetic waves with specific wavelengths.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] All electromagnetic waves travel at the same speed; therefore, shorter wavelengths are associated with high frequencies.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] All bodies generate and receive electromagnetic waves at the expense of heat exchange.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The microscopic theory of radiation is best known as the quantum theory and was first offered by Max Planck in 1900.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] According to this theory, energy emitted by a radiator is not continuous but is in the form of quanta.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Planck noted that energy was emitted in quanta of frequency of vibration similarly to the wave theory.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The energy *E* of an electromagnetic wave in vacuum is found by the expression *E* = *hf*, where *h* is the Planck constant and *f* is its frequency.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Bodies at higher temperatures emit radiation at higher frequencies with an increasing energy per quantum.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] While the propagation of electromagnetic waves of all wavelengths is often referred as "radiation", thermal radiation is often constrained to the visible and infrared regions.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] For engineering purposes, it may be stated that thermal radiation is a form of electromagnetic radiation which varies on the nature of a surface and its temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Radiation waves may travel in unusual patterns compared to conduction heat flow.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Radiation allows waves to travel from a heated body through a cold non-absorbing or partially absorbing medium and reach a warmer body again.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] An example is the case of the radiation waves that travel from the Sun to the Earth.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In 1924, Satyendra Nath Bose derived Planck's law from a quantum photon gas.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Bose and Albert Einstein established the concept of the photon as a boson that follows Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In the 1953, Sergei Rytov pioneered the study of thermal radiation in the near-field using the fluctuation–dissipation theorem.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] At short distance, below the thermal wavelength, he showed that heat transfer could surpass the limits given by Planck's blackbody theory.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In 1971, Dirk Polder and Michael Van Hove presented their work on near-field radiative heat transfer between closely spaced bodies based on Rytov's work and compared with experimental setups.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] A comparison of a thermal image (top) and an ordinary photograph (bottom).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The plastic bag is mostly transparent to long-wavelength infrared, but the man's glasses are opaque.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermal radiation emitted by a body at any temperature consists of a wide range of frequencies.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The frequency distribution is given by Planck's law of black-body radiation for an idealized emitter as shown in the diagram at top.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The dominant frequency (or color) range of the emitted radiation shifts to higher frequencies as the temperature of the emitter increases.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] For example, a *red hot* object radiates mainly in the long wavelengths (red and orange) of the visible band.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] If it is heated further, it also begins to emit discernible amounts of green and blue light, and the spread of frequencies in the entire visible range cause it to appear white to the human eye; it is *white hot*.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Even at a white-hot temperature of 2000 K, 99% of the energy of the radiation is still in the infrared.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] This is determined by Wien's displacement law.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In the diagram the peak value for each curve moves to the left as the temperature increases.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The total radiation intensity of a black body rises as the fourth power of the absolute temperature, as expressed by the Stefan–Boltzmann law.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] A kitchen oven, at a temperature about double room temperature on the absolute temperature scale (600 K vs.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] 300 K) radiates 16 times as much power per unit area.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] An object at the temperature of the filament in an incandescent light bulb—roughly 3000 K, or 10 times room temperature—radiates 10,000 times as much energy per unit area.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] As for photon statistics, thermal light obeys Super-Poissonian statistics.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] When the temperature of a body is high enough, its thermal radiation spectrum becomes strong enough in the visible range to visibly glow.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The visible component of thermal radiation is sometimes called *incandescence*, though this term can also refer to thermal radiation in general.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The term derives from the Latin verb *incandescere*, 'to glow white'.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In practice, virtually all solid or liquid substances start to glow around 798 K (525 °C; 977 °F), with a mildly dull red color, whether or not a chemical reaction takes place that produces light as a result of an exothermic process.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The incandescence does not vanish below that temperature, but it is too weak in the visible spectrum to be perceptible.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The rate of electromagnetic radiation emitted by a body at a given frequency is proportional to the rate that the body absorbs radiation at that frequency, a property known as reciprocity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thus, a surface that absorbs more red light thermally radiates more red light.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] This principle applies to all properties of the wave, including wavelength (color), direction, polarization, and even coherence.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] It is therefore possible to have thermal radiation which is polarized, coherent, and directional; though polarized and coherent sources are fairly rare in nature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermal radiation is one of the three principal mechanisms of heat transfer.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] It entails the emission of a spectrum of electromagnetic radiation due to an object's temperature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Other mechanisms are convection and conduction.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermal radiation is characteristically different from conduction and convection in that it does not require a medium and, in fact it reaches maximum efficiency in a vacuum.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermal radiation is a type of electromagnetic radiation which is often modeled by the propagation of waves.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] These waves have the standard wave properties of frequency, $\nu$ and wavelength, $\lambda$ which are related by the equation $\lambda ={\frac {c}{\nu }}$ where c is the speed of light in the medium.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The spectral absorption is equal to the emissivity $\epsilon$ ; this relation is known as Kirchhoff's law of thermal radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] If objects appear white (reflective in the visual spectrum), they are not necessarily equally reflective (and thus non-emissive) in the thermal infrared – see the diagram at the left.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Acrylic and urethane based white paints have 93% blackbody radiation efficiency at room temperature (meaning the term "black body" does not always correspond to the visually perceived color of an object).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] These materials that do not follow the "black color = high emissivity/absorptivity" caveat will most likely have functional spectral emissivity/absorptivity dependence.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Only truly *gray* systems (relative equivalent emissivity/absorptivity and no directional transmissivity dependence in *all* control volume bodies considered) can achieve reasonable steady-state heat flux estimates through the Stefan-Boltzmann law.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Encountering this "ideally calculable" situation is almost impossible (although common engineering procedures surrender the dependency of these unknown variables and "assume" this to be the case).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Optimistically, these "gray" approximations will get close to real solutions, as most divergence from Stefan-Boltzmann solutions is very small (especially in most standard temperature and pressure lab controlled environments).
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Reflectivity deviates from the other properties in that it is bidirectional in nature.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In other words, this property depends on the direction of the incident of radiation as well as the direction of the reflection.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Therefore, the reflected rays of a radiation spectrum incident on a real surface in a specified direction forms an irregular shape that is not easily predictable.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In practice, surfaces are often assumed to reflect either in a perfectly specular or a diffuse manner.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In a specular reflection, the angles of reflection and incidence are equal.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In diffuse reflection, radiation is reflected equally in all directions.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Reflection from smooth and polished surfaces can be assumed to be specular reflection, whereas reflection from rough surfaces approximates diffuse reflection.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In radiation analysis a surface is defined as smooth if the height of the surface roughness is much smaller relative to the wavelength of the incident radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Radiation emitted from a surface can propagate in any direction from the surface.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Irradiation can also be incident upon a surface from any direction.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The amount of irradiation on a surface is therefore dependent on the relative orientation of both the emitter and the receiver.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The parameter *radiation intensity,* I is used to quantify how much radiation makes it from one surface to another.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Radiation intensity is often modeled using a spherical coordinate system.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The total emissive power can also be found by integrating the *spectral emissive power* over all possible wavelengths.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] This is calculated as, $E=\int _{0}^{\infty }E_{\lambda }(\lambda )d\lambda$ where $\lambda$ represents wavelength.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The spectral emissive power can also be determined from the spectral intensity, $I_{\lambda }$ as follows, $E_{\lambda }(\lambda )=\pi I_{\lambda }(\lambda )$ where both spectral emissive power and emissive intensity are functions of wavelength.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] A "black body" is a body which has the property of allowing all incident rays to enter without surface reflection.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Blackbodies are idealized surfaces that act as the perfect absorber and emitter.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] They serve as the standard against which real surfaces are compared when characterizing thermal radiation.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The spectral intensity of a blackbody, $I_{\lambda ,b}$ was first determined by Max Planck.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] This formula mathematically follows from calculation of spectral distribution of energy in quantized electromagnetic field which is in complete thermal equilibrium with the radiating object.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Planck's law shows that radiative energy increases with temperature, and explains why the peak of an emission spectrum shifts to shorter wavelengths at higher temperatures.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] It can also be found that energy emitted at shorter wavelengths increases more rapidly with temperature relative to longer wavelengths.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The equation is derived as an infinite sum over all possible frequencies in a semi-sphere region.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The energy, $E=h\nu$ , of each photon is multiplied by the number of states available at that frequency, and the probability that each of those states will be occupied.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The solution of the above integral yields a remarkably elegant equation for the total emissive power of a blackbody, the *Stefan-Boltzmann law*, which is given as, $E_{b}=\sigma T^{4}$ where $\sigma$ is the *Steffan-Boltzmann constant*.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] For surfaces which are not black bodies, one has to consider the (generally frequency dependent) emissivity factor $\epsilon (\nu )$ .
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] This factor has to be multiplied with the radiation spectrum formula before integration.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] This type of theoretical model, with frequency-independent emissivity lower than that of a perfect black body, is often known as a *grey body*.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] For frequency-dependent emissivity, the solution for the integrated power depends on the functional form of the dependence, though in general there is no simple expression for it.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Practically speaking, if the emissivity of the body is roughly constant around the peak emission wavelength, the gray body model tends to work fairly well since the weight of the curve around the peak emission tends to dominate the integral.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Calculation of radiative heat transfer between groups of objects, including a 'cavity' or 'surroundings' requires solution of a set of simultaneous equations using the radiosity method.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] In these calculations, the geometrical configuration of the problem is distilled to a set of numbers called view factors, which give the proportion of radiation leaving any given surface that hits another specific surface.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] These calculations are important in the fields of solar thermal energy, boiler and furnace design and raytraced computer graphics.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] The *net* radiative heat transfer from one surface to another is the radiation leaving the first surface for the other minus that arriving from the second surface.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Formulas for radiative heat transfer can be derived for more particular or more elaborate physical arrangements, such as between parallel plates, concentric spheres and the internal surfaces of a cylinder.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermal radiation is an important factor of many engineering applications, especially for those dealing with high temperatures.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Sunlight is the incandescence of the "white hot" surface of the Sun.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Electromagnetic radiation from the sun has a peak wavelength of about 550 nm, and can be harvested to generate heat or electricity.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Thermal radiation can be concentrated on a tiny spot via reflecting mirrors, which concentrating solar power takes advantage of.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Instead of mirrors, Fresnel lenses can also be used to concentrate radiant energy.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] Either method can be used to quickly vaporize water into steam using sunlight.
[src:heat-transfer-physics/thermal-radiation] For example, the sunlight reflected from mirrors heats the PS10 Solar Power Plant, and during the day it can heat water to 285 °C (558 K; 545 °F).
